\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 2.               Trichomanes}                L.
\par   

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By D.A. Webb.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like Hymenophyllum, but with stouter, more hairy rhizomes, larger, erect, more compoundly pinnatisect leaves, and elongate, cylindrical sori, of which the basal part is protected by tubular, slightly 2-lipped indusium, the apical part eventually protruding and persisting in the form of a bristle-like receptacle after the sporangia have fallen off.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Copeland,{\i  Philipp. Jour. Sci.} ({\i Bot}.) {\b 64:} 1-188 (1937), has divided this large genus into numerous smaller genera; in this treatment the European species is assigned to the genus{\i  Vandenboschia} Copel.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. T. speciosum} Willd., {\i Sp. Pl.}{\b  5}({\b 1}): 514 (1810) ({\i T. radicans} auct., non Swartz). Rhizome 2- 4 mm in diameter, covered with black hairs. Leaves 20-35(-50) cm, the winged petiole about equalling the ovate, deeply 3- or 4-pinnatisect lamina; ultimate segments oblong, obtuse, entire, disposed symmetrically, not unilaterally as in {\i Hymenophyllum.} 2n = 144. {\i By waterfalls, at mouths of caves, and in similar damp, dark situations. Extreme west of Europe, eastwards to the Pyrenees}. Az Br Ga Hb Hs It [Lu].
\par

