\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b  12.       POLYPODIACEAE}
\par     

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  Edit. †D.H. Valentine & D.M. Moore.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Rhizome polystelic or solenostelic, with opaque scales. Leaves 2-ranked on the upper side of the rhizome and articulated to it; petiole with 1-3 major vascular strands. Sori superficial, without indusium; spores bilateral.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 1.                Polypodium}                L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †D.H. Valentine (Ed. 1) revised by J.R. Akeroyd & A.C. Jermy (Ed. 2).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Rhizome creeping. Leaves uniform; lamina pinnatifid or pinnate, glabrous, without scales; pinnae entire or dentate, the veins free. Sori orbicular or elliptical, without indusium.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Literature: M.G. Shivas,{\i  Jour. Linn. Soc. London} ({\i Bot}.){\b  58:} 13-38 (1961). R.H. Roberts,{\i  Fern Gaz.}{\b  12}: 69-74 (1980).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 In Europe the genus consists of a polyploid complex in which four species can be recognized. These all have deeply pinnatifid leaves up to 50 cm or more in length; the lamina is longer than the petiole, and the pinnae are usually alternate, with 5-28 on each side. The sori are arranged in 1 row on each side of the midrib of the pinna. All the species grow on rocks and walls, or, in the wetter parts of Europe, as epiphytes on trees.
\par

